<bor> sup all
<bor> i just received my wii. it already came presoftmodded. im new to softmodding and have a lot of reading up to do. but right now i just want to play some games. so im about to go to the store to buy an external HDD (WD Passport). and im wondering if i need to pick up an SD card aswell. do i need one for installing homebrew and modifying stuff or will a USB HDD be enough?
<bor> also, i have already experienced that back-up dvd's run at slower speeds and can cause stuttering. if i rip these backup games to HDD, will that stop the stuttering?
<lukegb> Austin: ha!
<DasTier> yes
<lukegb> !rules
<IOS61> lukegb: You are now being sent the rules. Please check for a tab/window/button labelled 'IOS61'
<bor> to both?
<DasTier> bor: an sd card makes it easier but is not needed per se, but I'd highly recommend getting one since none of the guides tell you how to boot without one
<DasTier> also, for certain steps the sd card is required, so if you ran into one of those, you'd need one no matter
<bor> alright, i doubt i will do much modifying to my system tho, as its a korean box and i read they are easiest to brick
<DasTier> ie. you can setup homebrew channel and others to use a harddisk but you can only install homebrew channel from SD
<bor> ah i see
<DasTier> they are just as easy to brick as any other wii, if you use an US update on a korean wii, that's a brick. If you use EU update on a US wii, that's a brick
<DasTier> the thing is just that so many people try to install US firmware on korean wiis
<bor> mkay
<bor> i have US firmware on it i think
<bor> or english firmware
<DasTier> there is an English hack, but it's still korean firmware inside
<bor> doubt the korean version will come with an english language pack
<bor> ah
<bor> and ehm, what file system for the HDD do you recommend?
<DasTier> fat32 so that homebrew channel can work with it
<DasTier> ntfs is read-only and wbfs is isos-only
<bor> but that has filesize limitations
<DasTier> so if you want to NOT use an sd card you will need fat32
<bor> and i already saw that super smash bros for example is 7GB
<DasTier> isos on the disk are stored in .wbfs files which are split in chunks of 1-2GB
<bor> USB Loader GX is installed on it already
<DasTier> but of course you're right, some people recommend ntfs to get around the 2GB limitation, but no wii app can write to ntfs
<bor> if i install games with that, will that auto split the games in parts?
<DasTier> depends on the version, most people here recommend using cfgloader instead of GX
<bor> k
<bor> any risks of bricking the box if i connect it to the internet?
<bor> obv i wont install a new firmware when prompted
<bor> but other than that, any risks?
<DasTier> firmware 4.3 doesn't allow you to disable auto updating anymore, but if that wii has 4.3 you'll run into many other problems anyway, I doubt anyone with a sane mind would install 4.3 on a softmodded wii
<bor> i think i have 4.1
<bor> it said 4.1u in the wii settings menu anyway
<DasTier> that's what you'd end up with when following most of the existing guides, yes
<DasTier> oh?
<DasTier> 4.1u is the US firmware, I wonder what the previous owner did to install that without bricking
<bor> it came from a shop in bangkok, he didnt speak much english ;)
<bor> how do i install the games on the HDD anyway. is it just a matter of dragging the ISO's from my computer to the HDD, plug it into my wii and run USB Loader GX to install? or do i need a WBFS manager?
<DasTier> wbfs manager is for wbfilesystem formatted drives, wii backup manager is for fat/ntfs
<bor> cool thanks
<bor> will read up on that
<DasTier> both gx and cfgloader can dump actual disks to the drive too if it's writable (not ntfs)
<DasTier> ? list
<bor> ? list
<DasTier> no factoid for wii backup manager
<bor> ? hddcompatibility
<DasTier> ^Wulfgar^ usually posts a link to it as long as he's not asleep ;)
<bor> he wrote it?
<DasTier> no he's just usually very active in here, just now it's the middle of the night for him I think
<bor> right right

<IOS61> Smash Stack is an exploit from Comex that uses a flaw in the custom stages in Super Smash Bros. Brawl (NTSC) to load unauthorized code on the Wii. It was released on August 20, 2009. It works for all System Menu versions.
<lukegb> !wb Indiana Pwns
<IOS61> Indiana Pwns: http://wiibrew.org/wiki/Indiana_Pwns
<IOS61> The Indiana Pwns is a safe way to enable homebrew on a Wii without hardware modification. The Indiana Pwns is achieved by playing a hacked game save for LEGO Indiana Jones which executes a homebrew application from an external SD card. Examples of such homebrew .elf or .dol files can be found on the List of homebrew applications|Homebrew applications page. The Indiana Pwns was created by Team Twiizers.

<Quanyails> 7Problem is if you have, let's say, a quarter-rest, quarter rest, quarter rest, and a quarter note. On another layer, you have quarter rest, quarter rest, quarter rest, eighth rest, and eighth note.
<Quanyails> 7Or if you want, fill in one set of quarter rests with notes.
<Creideiki> Well... there is a nice way of getting around the problem... for a print out.
<Creideiki> One simple hides one set of rests and then just moves the other rests downward/upward to fill the blanks.

<Creideiki> Yep.
<Quanyails> 7How? o.o

I would think that a good dynamic method would be to keep all first statements of a melodic fragment in a louder volume with the restatements in a quieter tone; also, a hint for a sudden increase in the volume of a note use that accidental that looks like a Greek capital lambda.
